{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_8","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -c 'rg -n \"TODO|FIXME|Milestone|lighthouse|playwright|coverage|frontend\" docs/specs docs/PROJECT_STATUS.md frontend tests test spec specs'","aggregated_output":"rg: tests: No such file or directory (os error 2)\nrg: test: No such file or directory (os error 2)\nrg: spec: No such file or directory (os error 2)\nrg: specs: No such file or directory (os error 2)\ndocs/PROJECT_STATUS.md:7:- Active spec + milestone: <e.g. docs/specs/base.md → Milestone 2>\ndocs/specs/frontend.md:11:1. Milestone <name>\ndocs/specs/frontend.md:14:- Link to which [docs/plan.md](../plan.md) **Milestone** this addresses\ndocs/specs/frontend.md:20:- Definition of done: <command/test that exits 0 when met, e.g. `pnpm --prefix harness run test:file -- frontend/main.test.ts`>\nfrontend/package.json:2:  \"name\": \"frontend\",\nfrontend/package.json:17:    \"test\": \"pnpm test:coverage\",\nfrontend/package.json:18:    \"test:coverage\": \"vitest run --config ../harness/vitest.config.js --coverage --coverage.include=\\\"frontend/**/*.ts\\\" ../frontend/*.test.ts\",\nfrontend/package.json:20:    \"typecheck\": \"pnpm --prefix ../harness run typecheck:frontend\"\nfrontend/package.json:26:    \"@axe-core/playwright\": \"latest\",\nfrontend/package.json:27:    \"@playwright/test\": \"latest\",\nfrontend/calculator-writeup.html:7:<meta name=\"description\" content=\"Why an AI VRAM calculator — not a todo list — is the right target for an agent loop that writes frontend code.\">\nfrontend/calculator-writeup.html:231:    <p class=\"sub\">I built an AI VRAM calculator in TypeScript to test frontend agent loops. It was the right kind of mistake.</p>\nfrontend/calculator-writeup.html:240:    <p class=\"lead\">I built an AI VRAM calculator because I needed a sample app for TypeScript frontend loops. That turned out to be the right kind of mistake: calculators force generated frontends to deal with real state, real math, real copy, and real edge cases.</p>\nfrontend/calculator-writeup.html:244:    <p>This post is about why that app &mdash; and not a todo list &mdash; is the right target for an agent loop that writes frontend code.</p>\nfrontend/calculator-writeup.html:256:      <li><strong>Tests matter because money does.</strong> People may buy hardware based on this output. That reframes 100% branch coverage from vanity metric to floor.</li>\nfrontend/calculator-writeup.html:263:      <li><strong>Gates catch boring, real issues.</strong> Eighteen checks &mdash; prettier, eslint, stylelint, typecheck, semgrep, 100%-coverage units, the full Playwright matrix, Lighthouse budgets. Almost nothing it rejected was interesting. All of it was real.</li>\nfrontend/calculator-writeup.html:269:    <p>Good frontend agent loops need a product-shaped target: something with state that interacts, math that can be checked, copy that carries meaning, and users who would notice. A calculator is a cheat code &mdash; the domain supplies the rigor, and the loop either meets it or fails visibly.</p>\nfrontend/tests/home.spec.ts:1:import { expect, test } from \"@playwright/test\";\nfrontend/public/llms.txt:3:LoopGate JS, also known as loopgate_js, is a TypeScript and Vite frontend\nfrontend/public/llms.txt:9:edit frontend code, and commit only after passing guardrails such as ESLint,\nfrontend/public/llms.txt:10:Stylelint, HTML validation, strict TypeScript, Vitest coverage, Playwright,\n","exit_code":2,"status":"failed"}}
