{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_21","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -c \"sed -n '180,320p' frontend/calculator-writeup.html\"","aggregated_output":"    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);\n  }\n  ul.notes li::before {\n    content: \"\\2014\";\n    position: absolute;\n    left: 0;\n    color: var(--stamp);\n    font-family: var(--mono);\n  }\n  ul.notes li strong { color: var(--accent-ink); }\n\n  blockquote.pull {\n    border: none;\n    padding: 0;\n    margin: 0.4rem auto;\n    text-align: center;\n  }\n  blockquote.pull p {\n    font-size: clamp(1.25rem, 1rem + 1.4vw, 1.8rem);\n    line-height: 1.28;\n    font-weight: 600;\n    letter-spacing: -0.01em;\n    max-width: 26ch;\n    margin: 0 auto;\n    text-wrap: balance;\n  }\n\n  .colophon {\n    font-family: var(--mono);\n    font-size: 0.78rem;\n    line-height: 1.6;\n    color: var(--slate);\n    border-top: 3px double var(--ink);\n    margin-top: 3rem;\n    padding-top: 1.5rem;\n    max-width: var(--measure);\n  }\n  .colophon strong { color: var(--ink); font-weight: 700; }\n</style>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n<div class=\"page\">\n  <div class=\"topbar\">\n    <a class=\"site-link\" href=\"/\">Rox dT</a>\n    <a class=\"site-link\" href=\"https://aideploymentcalculator.vercel.app/\">Try the calculator &rarr;</a>\n  </div>\n\n  <header class=\"masthead\">\n    <p class=\"eyebrow\">Field Notes &middot; On Loops</p>\n    <h1>A Frontend Loop Needs a Real App</h1>\n    <p class=\"sub\">I built an AI VRAM calculator in TypeScript to test frontend agent loops. It was the right kind of mistake.</p>\n    <p class=\"byline\">\n      <span>By Roxana del Toro</span>\n      <span>Loop engineering</span>\n      <span>Calculator, not todo</span>\n    </p>\n  </header>\n\n  <div class=\"flow\">\n    <p class=\"lead\">I built an AI VRAM calculator because I needed a sample app for TypeScript frontend loops. That turned out to be the right kind of mistake: calculators force generated frontends to deal with real state, real math, real copy, and real edge cases.</p>\n\n    <p>The app is live at <a href=\"https://aideploymentcalculator.vercel.app/\">aideploymentcalculator.vercel.app</a>. You give it a model size, precision, workload, and deployment mode; it gives you a VRAM estimate, a hardware tier, a rough speed, and the assumptions it used to get there. Everything runs in the browser. There is no backend.</p>\n\n    <p>This post is about why that app &mdash; and not a todo list &mdash; is the right target for an agent loop that writes frontend code.</p>\n\n    <h2><span class=\"kicker\">Why this app</span>The domain supplies the rigor</h2>\n    <p>VRAM estimation is a real question people ask before spending real money. &ldquo;Will a 70B model fit on the GPU I&rsquo;m about to buy?&rdquo; has a checkable answer, and getting it wrong is embarrassing in a way a mislabeled todo item never is.</p>\n    <p>More importantly for a loop benchmark, the domain has <em>naturally</em> interacting inputs: model size, precision, quantization overhead, context window, batch size, KV-cache precision, execution mode (inference vs LoRA vs QLoRA vs full training), MoE routing, memory sharding. These aren&rsquo;t invented complexity &mdash; they&rsquo;re the actual variables of the actual problem, and they interact. QLoRA pins you to 4-bit. Training modes hide inference-only fields. MoE changes speed but not resident memory. A Local/Edge profile that outgrows every consumer card needs to <em>say so</em> instead of cheerfully recommending a datacenter accelerator.</p>\n\n    <blockquote class=\"pull\"><p>A loop can fake its way through a todo app. It cannot fake its way through this.</p></blockquote>\n\n    <h2><span class=\"kicker\">Why it beats a todo app</span>The failures are visible</h2>\n    <ul class=\"notes\">\n      <li><strong>Incorrect math is visible.</strong> 70B at fp16 is 140 GB of weights; AdamW mixed precision is ~16 bytes per parameter. Anyone in the field can eyeball the output &mdash; and so does the parity suite, which drives four canonical scenarios through real browser controls.</li>\n      <li><strong>The UI complexity is natural.</strong> The uncheck path of a checkbox whose default is <code>true</code> was a real bug: HTML forms omit unchecked boxes, normalization fell back to the default, and Gradient Checkpointing could never be turned off. Tests passed, the gate was green, and the bug shipped &mdash; because nobody wrote the <em>uncheck</em> test.</li>\n      <li><strong>Tests matter because money does.</strong> People may buy hardware based on this output. That reframes 100% branch coverage from vanity metric to floor.</li>\n      <li><strong>Accessibility is the product.</strong> The suite runs six browser projects, phone to 2560px. That matrix caught a WebKit bug: Safari never restyles a sibling when a <code>&lt;meter&gt;</code> attribute changes, so the fit meter stayed wrong for every real Safari user while Chrome looked perfect.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h2><span class=\"kicker\">What the loop taught</span>Specs, gates, and copy</h2>\n    <ul class=\"notes\">\n      <li><strong>Specs beat vibes.</strong> Every behavior worth having was written down before it was generated; the ones that weren&rsquo;t are the ones that churned.</li>\n      <li><strong>Gates catch boring, real issues.</strong> Eighteen checks &mdash; prettier, eslint, stylelint, typecheck, semgrep, 100%-coverage units, the full Playwright matrix, Lighthouse budgets. Almost nothing it rejected was interesting. All of it was real.</li>\n      <li><strong>Copy is product logic when numbers are uncertain.</strong> &ldquo;Fits on one 24 GB card: 19.0 GB uses 93% of its 20.4 GB usable VRAM&rdquo; took more revisions than the math. An estimate without its assumptions is indistinguishable from a wrong one.</li>\n      <li><strong>Quality drifts upward when checks are strict.</strong> The gate refuses <code>eslint-disable</code>, unstages forbidden paths at commit, runs the whole matrix on every push. &ldquo;Demo app&rdquo; stopped being accurate without anyone deciding it should.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h2><span class=\"kicker\">The takeaway</span>Pick a product-shaped target</h2>\n    <p>Good frontend agent loops need a product-shaped target: something with state that interacts, math that can be checked, copy that carries meaning, and users who would notice. A calculator is a cheat code &mdash; the domain supplies the rigor, and the loop either meets it or fails visibly.</p>\n    <p>This one ended up as both: a tool I actually use before recommending hardware, and the proving ground that shaped <a href=\"https://github.com/rxdt/loopgate-harness\">LoopGate</a>&rsquo;s checks. The todo app never stood a chance.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <p class=\"colophon\">\n    The calculator is live at <a href=\"https://aideploymentcalculator.vercel.app/\"><strong>aideploymentcalculator.vercel.app</strong></a>; source at <a href=\"https://github.com/rxdt/ai_deployment_calculator\">rxdt/ai_deployment_calculator</a>. The harness it hardened: <a href=\"https://github.com/rxdt/loopgate-harness\">rxdt/loopgate-harness</a>.\n    <br><a href=\"/\">Back to Rox dT</a>\n  </p>\n\n</div>\n\n</body>\n</html>\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_22","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -c \"sed -n '320,500p' frontend/engineering-the-loop.html\"","aggregated_output":"    font-size: 0.78rem;\n    line-height: 1.6;\n    color: var(--slate);\n    border-top: 3px double var(--ink);\n    margin-top: 3.5rem;\n    padding-top: 1.5rem;\n    max-width: var(--measure);\n    margin-inline: auto;\n  }\n  .colophon strong { color: var(--ink); font-weight: 700; }\n</style>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n<div class=\"page\">\n  <div class=\"topbar\">\n    <a class=\"site-link\" href=\"/\">Rox dT</a>\n    <a class=\"site-link canonical-link\" href=\"https://dev.to/rxdt/stop-prompting-start-engineering-the-loop-325d\" rel=\"canonical\">Originally on dev.to &rarr;</a>\n  </div>\n\n  <header class=\"masthead\">\n    <p class=\"eyebrow\">Field Notes &middot; On Harnesses</p>\n    <h1>Stop Prompting, Start Engineering the Loop</h1>\n    <p class=\"sub\">The hardest problem in AI-assisted coding isn&rsquo;t picking a model. It&rsquo;s engineering the loop around it.</p>\n    <p class=\"byline\">\n      <span>By Roxana del Toro</span>\n      <span>Loop engineering</span>\n      <span>Verification debt</span>\n    </p>\n  </header>\n\n  <div class=\"col\">\n    <div class=\"flow\">\n      <p class=\"lead\">The hardest problem in AI-assisted coding isn&rsquo;t picking a model. It&rsquo;s engineering the loop around it. It will soon be quaint to ask <em>which model is best?</em> As reasoning and tool-use models converge in capabilities, the model matters less than the harness you build for it. This month alone: Anthropic released Fable, yanked it because guardrails &lsquo;could not be trusted,&rsquo; then re-released it. OpenAI dropped three frontier models just this week. And Meta shipped its first agentic model. Yet agentic coding issues continue.</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <aside class=\"margin\">\n      <span class=\"label\">Thesis</span>\n      <h3>The model is rented. Your harness is an asset.</h3>\n      <p>A strong model in a weak system is unruly and expensive. A weaker model in a disciplined one ships useful work, at lower cost and lower risk.</p>\n    </aside>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"col section\" style=\"margin-top:3.2rem;padding-top:2.6rem;border-top:1px solid var(--rule);\">\n    <div class=\"flow\">\n      <span class=\"kicker\">I &middot; Complete the circle</span>\n      <h2>Loop Engineering</h2>\n      <p>Yes, the model matters. But the system around it increasingly matters more. A strong model inside a weak system can be unruly and expensive, or even downright destructive. A weaker model in a disciplined system ships more useful work, at lower cost and lower risk.</p>\n      <p>That&rsquo;s why two IDEs running the same model feel nothing alike. One reads the right files, makes a focused change, runs the relevant tests, and reports uncertainty. The other burns context, edits unrelated code, retries failed approaches, and declares victory.</p>\n\n      <blockquote class=\"pull\"><p>The difference isn&rsquo;t the model. It&rsquo;s the harness.</p></blockquote>\n\n      <p>Benchmarks measure what a model can do under controlled conditions. The same model posts different scores on the same benchmark depending on the platform. But developers don&rsquo;t care about marketing numbers. They care what a system does inside a messy repository.</p>\n      <p>So the competitive edge isn&rsquo;t access to the smartest model. It&rsquo;s the best execution environment around whatever model you have.</p>\n    </div>\n    <aside class=\"margin\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"background:none;border:none;padding:0;\"></aside>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"col section\" style=\"margin-top:3.2rem;padding-top:2.6rem;border-top:1px solid var(--rule);\">\n    <div class=\"flow\">\n      <span class=\"kicker\">II &middot; Two disciplines</span>\n      <h2>Prompt engineering vs. loop engineering</h2>\n      <p>Prompting is a single request. Loop engineering is the operating system around the request.</p>\n      <p>Developers need to stop treating agents like chatbots that need elaborate instructions. A giant spec is not a workflow. It&rsquo;s an undocumented program with weak control flow and no failure handling.</p>\n      <p>Agents have their own ADHD. They keep working after the useful work is done: refactoring unrelated code, rewriting tests, &ldquo;cleaning up.&rdquo; You know the moment. You set the task up perfectly, stepped away from the terminal, and came back to a <strong>WTF?!</strong> diff.</p>\n\n      <blockquote class=\"pull\"><p>More prompting doesn&rsquo;t fix this. Boundaries do.</p></blockquote>\n\n      <p>Stop prompting a model to behave. An agent without a harness is a driver on a road with no lanes, no signs, no speed limit &mdash; just a post-it called <code>AGENTS.md</code>. A harness paints road lanes, puts up stoplights, adds a highway patrol. Imagine driving in a foreign country where roads didn&rsquo;t have signs or markers. Do you drive on the left or the right, or is it all one road?</p>\n      <p>A harness loop defines the task, gathers context, plans, makes a bounded change, runs checks, inspects failures, retries selectively, records decisions, and STOPS at a success condition or budget limit. Instructions should not just tell agents &ldquo;Do not do.&rdquo; A harness should detect and stop changes. It should restrict paths, inspect diffs, enforce scope, and reject work that violates a contract.</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <aside class=\"margin\">\n      <span class=\"label\">The road metaphor</span>\n      <p>No harness &rarr; a driver on a road with no lanes, no signs, no speed limit. Just a post-it called <code>AGENTS.md</code>.</p>\n      <p>A harness paints the lanes, puts up the stoplights, and adds the highway patrol.</p>\n    </aside>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"col\">\n    <div class=\"flow\" style=\"margin-top:1.4rem;\">\n      <div class=\"errata\">\n        <span class=\"label\">On the author&rsquo;s harness</span>\n        <p>My <a href=\"https://github.com/rxdt/loopgate-harness\">Python harness</a> and the TypeScript port are wrappers around a bash loop with a hard timeout. None of it is clever. It enforces boring coding standards humans try to follow &mdash; and agents do, when guardrails are set. Like most software, it&rsquo;s a work in progress.</p>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n    <aside class=\"margin\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"background:none;border:none;padding:0;\"></aside>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"col section\" style=\"margin-top:3.2rem;padding-top:2.6rem;border-top:1px solid var(--rule);\">\n    <div class=\"flow\">\n      <span class=\"kicker\">III &middot; The bottleneck moved</span>\n      <h2>Verification Debt</h2>\n      <p>Agents generate code faster than humans can verify it. The bottleneck has moved from generation to diff review, and we&rsquo;re accruing <strong>verification debt</strong> &mdash; like technical debt, except it piles up before you&rsquo;ve proven anything works. A 1,000-line agent patch compiles. It passes the tests the agent wrote. Neither proves intended behavior. Maybe it misunderstood the requirement. Mocked away the hard part. Quietly changed a public interface.</p>\n      <p>The cost is measurable. In METR&rsquo;s trial, experienced open-source developers took <strong>19% longer</strong> with AI tools while thinking they&rsquo;d been <strong>20% faster</strong>. Review sucks time. But going fast on a merry-go-round isn&rsquo;t speed.</p>\n      <p>And the backlash against &ldquo;AI slop&rdquo; is earned. Five agents don&rsquo;t produce five times the output. They produce conflicting abstractions and five times the review burden. Engineers were never graded on lines of code. There is elegance in less. Yet &ldquo;tasks completed&rdquo; is now a boast, and a dangerous metric.</p>\n      <p>Verification belongs inside the loop: executable acceptance criteria, independent tests, static analysis, type checks, security scans, and human review proportional to risk.</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <aside class=\"margin\">\n      <span class=\"label\">The METR number</span>\n      <h3>&minus;19% slower. Felt +20% faster.</h3>\n      <p>Experienced open-source developers, using AI tools, took 19% longer &mdash; while believing they&rsquo;d been 20% faster. The review burden negates the speed gain.</p>\n    </aside>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"col section\" style=\"margin-top:3.2rem;padding-top:2.6rem;border-top:1px solid var(--rule);\">\n    <div class=\"flow\">\n      <span class=\"kicker\">IV &middot; Death by defensible changes</span>\n      <h2>Repo damage: how AI agents degrade a codebase</h2>\n      <p>The failure that should make you nervous isn&rsquo;t one bad patch. It&rsquo;s cumulative degradation. An agent solves today&rsquo;s narrow task while making the codebase harder to maintain. Every change is individually defensible. The sum? Entropy.</p>\n      <p>You see it when agents operate without context. They recreate functions that already exist because they never looked. They route around architectural constraints they don&rsquo;t understand. They add dependencies for problems an installed library already solves.</p>\n      <p>Fixing this takes more than updating <code>AGENTS.md</code>. The workflow is controlled delegation &mdash; a harness with local quality gates:</p>\n      <ul class=\"checklist\">\n        <li><strong>Before the edit:</strong> the system understands the repository.</li>\n        <li><strong>During:</strong> it constrains the scope.</li>\n        <li><strong>After:</strong> it evaluates the diff as a change to the whole, not an answer to a prompt.</li>\n      </ul>\n      <p>Humans build the harness. Agents work inside it. The harness manages context, tools, permissions, budgets, checkpoints, and verification. That makes engineering the loop central work.</p>\n    </div>\n    <aside class=\"margin\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"background:none;border:none;padding:0;\"></aside>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"col section\" style=\"margin-top:3.2rem;padding-top:2.6rem;border-top:1px solid var(--rule);\">\n    <div class=\"flow\">\n      <span class=\"kicker\">V &middot; The checklist</span>\n      <h2>Audit your AI coding loop</h2>\n      <p>The best developers won&rsquo;t write the most code. They&rsquo;ll build the loops that write the best code. The model is rented. Your harness is an asset.</p>\n      <p><strong>No harness? Big problem.</strong> Run the audit:</p>\n      <ul class=\"checklist\">\n        <li>Every run has a hard budget: time, tokens, iterations.</li>\n        <li>Agents can only touch scoped paths.</li>\n        <li>Acceptance criteria are executable and written before agents start.</li>\n        <li>Tests do not come from the agent that wrote the code.</li>\n        <li>Agents stop on success.</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n    <aside class=\"margin\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"background:none;border:none;padding:0;\"></aside>\n  </div>\n\n  <p class=\"colophon\">\n    Originally published on <a href=\"https://dev.to/rxdt/stop-prompting-start-engineering-the-loop-325d\">dev.to</a>. Reference harness implementations, in Python and TypeScript, are open source: <a href=\"https://github.com/rxdt/loopgate-harness\"><strong>rxdt/loopgate-harness</strong></a>.\n    <br><a href=\"/\">Back to Rox dT</a>\n  </p>\n\n</div>\n\n</body>\n</html>\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
